John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, and this continues in 2018 with another superb exam performance that is only enhanced by individual and collective success in sports disciplines, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an education sector that can compile and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language they can understand, your words get to them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year's exams, we see that languages come first with the highest scores for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have achieved the A grade.
Data collected from 74 members of SCIS schools showed that 72% of students achieved an A score in Chinese, with the same score having 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice by students receive the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that 17% of the reasons employers have difficulty finding employees indicated insufficient language competences.
Because of this, more and more foreign language proficiency is becoming mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require proficiency in a foreign language, making these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masters a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered a similar skill that remains for life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multi-lingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adult UK citizens in 2013, 75% were not fluent in a foreign language well enough to be able to conduct a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reached a double-digit percentage with an indicator of 15%.
That is why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Fluency in several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in terms of languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered more important to the UK in a future plan by 2020, for example Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child has, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with educators being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, regardless of what the future holds.
At the moment, there is no denying that in a global business environment, languages continue to have an incredibly important role for the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
Indeed, modern languages should actually be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools
