North Korea says 'no way' to disarm unilaterally, without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that the continued sanctions deepened distrust of the United States, and there was no way the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
At the annual general meeting of the world organization, Ri Yong-hou said that "significant measures of good will" have been taken in the past year, for example, we are suspending nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security, and under no circumstances will we be the first to disarm unilaterally."
While Ri was expressing North Korea's familiar complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking stepwise measures, his statement seemed significant as he did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement from Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for "nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump gave guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea was seeking an official end to the Korean War of 1950-1953, but the U.S. said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'eliminating nuclear weapons first' and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal through coercion, and even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream of those who don't know us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the U.S. leader stressed through the U.N. earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the removal of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill.
However, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles at the US mainland was inevitable after "evil President" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea removes nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there was no deadline for this and said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until full, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament takes place."
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo visited North Korea three times, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but after only a few hours North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea vowed to destroy a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
According to him, Kim told him that the "appropriate measures" he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wished to achieve normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year makes all students sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of "all-night" learning with the help of caffeine.
A lecturer found that students at the world's number one university often don't even think twice when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, has drafted the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"Finally, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are they only telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one ever spoke to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after students were found to be suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one part, there is an image of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers, and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of bedtime routines.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke," added Prof. Keisler.
The culture of pride of "all-night learning" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient and quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says - even in order to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, causing them to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaysler in preparing the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says the course "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Kaysler recommends that students consider setting a bedtime and wake alarm and knowing the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to trouble falling asleep.
