The method involves extracting immune cells from the patient and modifying them in a laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers called HER2 and then re-inject into the patient.
According to Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "stimulates the growth of several types of cancer", including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and "teaching" them how to target cancer cells was used in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
