HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China reported a 14% jump in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
According to health services, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The majority of new cases are caused by sexual contacts, which marks a change compared to the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, China's health services said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, every year the number of those living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by 100,000.
HIV transmission through sexual contact is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
In 1997, homosexuality was decriminalized in China, but discrimination against people in KGBT communities is widespread.
According to surveys, due to conservative values, 70-90% of men who have had sexual encounters with men end up marrying women.
Many cases of disease transmission are due to improper protection in these relationships.
In 2003, the government of China pledged to provide universal access to HIV medication as part of efforts to address the problem.
