What is the Global Citizen Festival and does it help reduce poverty at all?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that has an impressive lineup of performers and performs an equally impressive mission: eradicating poverty around the world.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will bring together tens of thousands of people on the great Central Park lawn who will not only enjoy the performances of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Sean Mendes, but will also get to know the true purpose of the event - eliminating extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was launched in 2012, is a continuation of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to get a free ticket to the event (unless you want to pay for a VIP ticket), visitors had to complete a number of tasks or "actions" such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or otherwise connecting in order to help raise awareness of their goal of eradicating poverty.
But how successful was Global Citizen 12 years before it achieved its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert an ingenious way to convince them to demand action or is it just another case of so-called "clectiveism" - people think they're doing something significant when they sign an online petition or send a Twitter post?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million "actions" from its supporters, who insist on a multitude of different goals.
It says these actions have helped world leaders announce commitments and policies amounting to more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
