World Wide Web inventor plans to launch new internet to attack Google and Facebook
World Wide Web inventor Tim Berners-Lee is launching a venture that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds the Berners-Lee Solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was "world domination".
"We have to do it now," he said regarding the venture.
"This is a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own "online personal data repository" or POD.
It contains lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional instruments.
It looks like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are available through any browser, and at the same time it is all of them at the same time.
What is unique about the online repository of personal data is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it "giving authority to personal data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is for the company to put resources, processes and appropriate skills into helping Solid become accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, several developers contracted to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
