Germany Delays Launch of New Warship Again
The German Navy's newest frigate was scheduled to be commissioned in 2014 to replace outdated Cold War-era warships, but this will not happen until at least next year due to malfunctioning systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class brand of new frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted an army spokesman.
The vessel was scheduled to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships commissioned by the Navy in 2007 will replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - the latest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to the ports of residence.
However, the continuous delays mean that the avant-garde warships - rumored to allow Germany to demonstrate strength overseas - will already be old when they enter service, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated frigate F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that render the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
Software flaws are particularly important as Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is estimated to be twice as heavy as the ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project - including crew training - is also becoming a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) - out of the original 2.2 billion euros.
Problems with the latest frigates became particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces were shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the fleet was in fact "running out of ships capable of carrying out missions."
