He complained that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate could join the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret lives of bats
A new study carried out at a manor house in the Scottish Highlands aims to establish how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hopes are that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats as well as the brown arrowheads waterbeds at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the estate to track bat activities during the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all the recordings will establish the frequency of the call sounds of the bats, as well as which species make them.
A habitat map and report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
The risk to populations can be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, shelter inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave Manor in the Dumfries and Galloway area, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
Manor manager David Thompson says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a great pitch for bats," he noted.
"We have old buildings, very old trees and a finished suitable habitat.
But there's a lot more to bats that aren't known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stresses that it is important to check for the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of one refuge will kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, as we just don't know what's going on with their populations."
