Europe regained the championship crown in the tournament after the team, led by Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, reached the necessary 14.5 points that guaranteed victory over the United States.
The US star, Phil Mickelson, who performed poorly for most of the tournament, threw his first shot at the 16th hole (with a "par" 3) in the water, losing his match against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari performed well in all rounds, becoming one of four players in the tournament's history to reach a 5-0-0 balance since the race was held in the current format after 1979.
American Jordan Spieth lost decisively with 5&4 to the player in the team of Europe, located at the lowest place in the rankings - Torbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
World ranking leader Dustin Johnson lost 2 and 1 to Ian Poulter of England, for whom this is probably the last participation of the Ryder Cup.
Spaniard Sergio Garcia, a veteran with eight Ryder Cup appearances, became the European with the most points earned in the tournament of all time, increasing his asset to 25.5 points this year.
"I don't usually cry, but today I can't help it.
It's been a rough year.
I am extremely grateful to Thomas for calling me and believing in me.
I'm so glad I can get the bowl up again.
In everything, the most important thing is the team and I am happy that I was able to help," shared the excited Garcia after the victory of Europe.
He passed the baton to fellow countryman John Ram, who beat American legend Tiger Woods 2&1 on singles on Sunday.
"I'm incredibly proud that I beat Tiger Woods, after all I grew up watching him play," said the 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost all four of his matches in France and his total Ryder Cup balance is now 13-21-3.
Strange statistics about one of the greatest players of all time, who won 14 major titles - an indicator by which he is second only to Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team struggled throughout the weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who showed high-class golf in all days of the tournament.
U.S. team captain Jim Furrick said after the team's disappointing performance: "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
At one point this morning, we cornered the Europa team.
There was a fight.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 of his players performed very well.
We will regroup, discuss important issues with the Professional Golfers Association of the United States and our Ryder Cup Committee, and look only forward.
I love these 12 boys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You can't help but take off your opponent's hat.
We were just outplayed."
New for the Red Tide: Concentrations Decline in Pinellas, Manotti and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in sections of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for stunting in the Pinellas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - this indicates a decrease in concentrations.
Watersheds with excessive red tide bloom extend approximately 130 miles along the coast, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Algae sections can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but are fewer than last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal area or slightly further inland in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations in Hillsboro County, prerequisites for high concentrations in Manotti County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coastal area or further inland in Sarasota County, prerequisites for moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coastal area or further inland in Lee County, as well as low concentrations in Collier County.
Reports of respiratory tract inflammation continue to be received in Pinellas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory tract inflammation in Northwest Florida.
